<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How many downspouts do I need?", answer: "IRC and gutter manufacturer tables limit one downspout per 35 linear feet of 5-inch K-style gutter, one per 50 feet of 6-inch, and one per 60 feet of 7-inch. For a 40 foot eave run with 5-inch gutter, you need 2 downspouts; with 6-inch gutter, just 1. Fewer downspouts lower cost and simplify drainage but require the larger gutter size." },
  { question: "5-inch vs 6-inch gutters — which is better?", answer: "5-inch K-style is the residential default and handles most roofs up to about 2,000 sq ft of drainage area. 6-inch K-style handles roughly 50 percent more water and is recommended for larger homes, steep roofs, or areas with intense rainfall. 6-inch costs 20 to 30 percent more material-wise but requires fewer downspouts, which often cancels out the upcharge. Switch to 6-inch if any of: roof area over 2,000 sq ft per side, pitch over 6:12, or annual rainfall over 50 inches." },
  { question: "How much do gutters cost?", answer: "Aluminum K-style gutters run 4 to 8 dollars per linear foot for materials, plus 3 to 6 dollars per foot for professional installation. Total installed cost is 7 to 14 dollars per linear foot for 5-inch aluminum, 9 to 16 dollars for 6-inch. Copper gutters are 3 to 5 times more expensive. For a 200 linear foot house with 8 downspouts, budget 1,500 to 3,500 dollars installed." },
  { question: "Do I include downspout length in my total?", answer: "Yes — downspout drops run from the gutter to the ground. A typical single-story drop is 10 feet, a two-story 20 feet. The calculator multiplies your downspout count by the drop length and adds it to gutter linear feet for a total material estimate. Also add elbows, outlets, hangers, and splash blocks as separate line items." },
  { question: "Can I install gutters myself?", answer: "Yes — seamless gutters require professional installation because the machine extrudes them on site, but sectional aluminum gutters are DIY-friendly. Expect to need a ladder, a tin snips, gutter seal, a drill, and hidden hangers (modern) or spike-and-ferrule (old-school). Measure eave lengths accurately, cut sections with small overlaps at seams, slope the run 1/4 inch per 10 linear feet toward downspouts, and seal every joint with gutter silicone." }
]) %>

